ownedComment.body: This attribute specifies if the target OS/MEs are allowed and/or required to reroute this SNC if there is a failure on this SNC, periodically to optimize the routes, of for any other reason. It is a target OS/ME implementation whether this is done using network routing protocols or if the target OS/MEs detect the failure and take appropriate action to attempt to fix the SNC. The NO value means that the target OS/MEs are not allowed to reroute the SNC. The YES value means that the target OS/MEs are allowed to reroute the SNC and are required to attempt to reroute it upon failure. The NA value is used when the requesting OS does not want to specify the exact target OS behaviour. In this case it is left up to the target OS to decide whether rerouting will be provided. It is also used if the target OS/MEs are allowed to reroute the SNC but not required to attempt to reroute it upon failure.

This object class represents a multi-layer SNPP (Subnetwork Point Pool) Link. The MLSNPPLink (Multi-Layer SNPP Link) structure is the abstraction of a set of control plane SNPP Links in different layered networks offered by the target OS to the requesting OS. Note that multi-layer does not imply client-server relationship, but flexible mapping at the same switching layer. The MLSNPPLink represents the relationship between a pair of MLSNPPs. The MLSNPPLink represents a set (>0) of SNPP Links. The SNPP link represents the relationship between a pair of SNPPs in different routing areas that are part of the same layer network. For more details see SD1-45_ASONControlPlaneManagement-Primer.
Traceability: R_TMF518_NRF_I_0096, R_TMF518_NRF_I_0097, R_TMF518_NRF_I_0098.

This object class represents a Multi Layer Routing Area (MLRA) that is managed by the target OS.
An MLRA consists of multiple congruent Routing Areas (RAs) at different layers. The Control Plane RA consists of a set of subordinate RAs, the SNPP Links that interconnect them, and the SNPPs representing the ends of the SNPP Links exiting that RA. The way that RAs and SNPP Links are grouped in RAs is entirely determined by the target OS.
MLRAs are organized in a hierarchical structure based upon "containment" (in which the lower level MLRAs are completely contained within a single higher level MLRA). The MLRA can contain other MLRAs and this recursion can continue as many times as necessary. A Top Level RA coincides with the whole Control Plane Network. The information on MLRA (subordinated MLRAs) can be accessed through operation on the containing MLRA.
Traceability: R_TMF518_NRF_I_0079, R_TMF518_NRF_I_0080.

ownedComment.body:
This object class represents a Call.
The call structure is the abstraction of a call. G.8080 defines a call as the association between endpoints that supports an instance of a service. As such, an end-to-end call is considered to consist of multiple call segments, depending on whether the call traverses multiple domains (signalling, routing or recovery domains included). For purposes of this interface call and call segments are identical.
The association between calls in a client/server layer relationship are coordinated by the layer NCC (Network Call Controller). This association can recur to mirror a set of "stacked" adaptations. The target OS interaction with the call is realized through the layer NCC at which the call was requested. Call Operations can only be done by the target OS that controls the call, this is by the OS that controls the originating points of the call.
A Call can exist in the context of a MultiLayer Subnetwork (MLSN) if the routing domain is equivalent to the MLSN domain. A Call can exist in the context of a Multi Layer Routing Area (MLRA) if the routing domain is spread over more than one MLSN domain. In both cases the Call is named by the EMS. It represents the association between endpoints in support of an instance of a service or an infrastructure trail.
A Call is a grouping object that is used to facilitate and manage (establish, modify, delete) a set of Subnetwork Connections (SNCs) that provide end-to-end transport of user information. Because the Call manages the set of Connections/SNCs as a group, it is possible to take diversity constraints between the individual Connections/SNCs into account when they are created/modified. Calls which exist in the context of an MLSN manage the SNCs directly.
Calls which exist in the context of an MLRA: - manage the SNCs indirectly via top-level Connections - manage the Connections indirectly via top-level Connections (refer to the Figure entitled "Example of Encapsulation Layer Link segments with off-network CPTPs" in the attached supporting document SD1-44_ConnectionlessTechnologyManagement.pdf).
There is a relationship between Calls and top-level Connections. Zero or more top-level Connections may be associated to a Call. A top-level Connection may not be part of more than one Call. The bandwidth of a Call is provided by one or more Connections.
Note: Creating a Call between Termination Points (TPs) in the same Managed Element is possible. Calls are expected to be identified globally.
Traceability: R_TMF518_NRF_I_0085, R_TMF518_NRF_I_0086.

ownedComment.body:
The Connection object represents the relationship between two Subnetwork Points (SNP) or Termination Points.
A Connection may encompass a sequence of Connections (which are referred to as Connection Segments, but not represented in this model) and thus create a recursive relationship between Connections (i.e., Connections supporting Connections). The Connection(s) at the highest level of recursion are referred to as top-level Connection(s).
Note that a Call may have one or more parallel top-level Connection(s).

ownedComment.body:
This attribute specifies if the target OS/MEs/Control Plane is allowed and/or required to reroute the Connection if there is a failure on the Connection, periodically to optimize the routes, or for any other reason. It is an target OS/ME/Control Plane implementation whether this is done using network routing protocols or if the target OS/ME/Control Plane detects the failure and takes appropriate action to attempt to fix the Connection.
The NO value means that the target OS/Control Plane is not allowed to reroute the Connection. The YES value means that the target OS/Control Plane is allowed to reroute the Connection and is required to attempt to reroute it upon failure. The NOT_APPLICABLE value is used when the requesting OS does not want to specify the exact target OS/Control Plane behaviour. In this case it is left up to the target OS/Control Plane to decide whether rerouting will be provided. It is also used if the target OS/Control Plane is allowed to reroute the Connection but not required to attempt to reroute it upon failure.
